    personalText: "The wine has gone warm in the glasses, and no one has thought to refill the water. Spring stalls outside, neither warm nor cold, the kind of hour that holds itself. Sofía sits very still at the corner of the table. Her phone lies face-up beside her hand, dark.\n\n\"You've been somewhere else all morning,\" one of them says, leaning in. \"Is it the divorce? You can tell us.\"\n\nShe turns the phone a quarter inch and turns it back. Says nothing. Someone laughs at the other end about a wedding ring, about lawyers, about how freeing it must feel.\n\nThe talk moves on. \"We had Vallarta booked,\" a woman is saying, \"and they made us reroute the whole thing. The advisories. My husband refused to go anywhere near Jalisco.\" Another voice agrees, too loud. \"It's not worth the risk anymore. Such a shame, it used to be lovely.\"\n\nSofía looks up.\n\nHer grandmother is in a town none of them could find on a map, in the hills above that coast, in a house where the phone sits on a shelf by the window. She has been calling since the early hours. The line rings and gives nothing back.\n\nYou keep returning to the particular silence of a voice you can no longer summon at will, the way absence sharpens before it softens.\n\nHer hands are folded in her lap now, pressed together to keep them from the table. The tremor lives there, contained, a small private weather under the cloth. The phone stays dark beside the bread.\n\n\"Anyway,\" the woman says, \"we found this gorgeous place instead. No comparison, but at least it's safe.\"\n\nSofía nods at nothing. Across the table they refill their glasses, comfortable, certain the day will hold. She watches the screen the way you watch breath in someone sleeping.\n\nSomewhere, her grandmother's phone rings into whatever room it's in.",
